dlSdlKCCSRI.title: Behind the Scenes: Waiting For Love Minecraft Note Block Video
dlSdlKCCSRI.description:
A behind the scenes video for the Minecraft note block remake of Waiting For Love by Avicii I made on my main channel. Watch that video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1tzJTMROH08

The command blocks for the actual note block song (the ones shown in the first few seconds of this video) were made first by using Minecraft Note block Studio to generate the note blocks (after arranging the song by ear myself) and then by converting the note blocks to command blocks using an MCEdit filter I made. The command blocks have /setblock commands to spawn note blocks and play them wirelessly.

The command blocks shown for most of the video are responsible for the mob choreography. I built them all manually (with a lot of copying and modifying parts of other commands). It took a very long time to set it all up (I'd guess somewhere around 50 hours), much more than I had anticipated beforehand.

Watch the official 360 music video for Waiting For Love here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=edcJ_JNeyhg

Thanks for watching!

FqrrEyMZ_xA.title: Dimitri Cervo - Guitar Concerto (III mov.)
FqrrEyMZ_xA.description:
Concerto para Violão e Orquestra de Câmara - Série Brasil 2010 n. 2. 
StudioClio, Porto Alegre, Brasil, UFRGS TV
Apoio: Bolsa Funarte de Estímulo à Criação Artística.

Dimitri Cervo (regência), Paulo Inda (violão solo), Paula Bujes (violino), Tiago Ellwanger (violino), Cosmas Grieneisen (viola), Pedro Huff (violoncelo), Ana Paula Freire (contrabaixo), André Mendes (flauta), Pablo Hernandez (oboé).

III. Maestoso

In this performance the String Orchestra was replaced by a String Quintet. The studio recording was matched with the images of live performance.

"It was followed by a very striking work by Dimitri Cervo... the Concerto for guitar and chamber orchestra, op. 31, ... this was probably the only truly tonal work in the entire festival, in a luxuriant D major for all three movements, and very idiomatically conceived for the guitar, with the low E tuned to D to facilitate ringing chords strummed in the tonic. The slow movement featured lyrically beautiful solos for flute and oboe over accompanimental figuration from the soloist. The concluding fast movement returned to a quick dance topic, and throughout the figuration for the strings reflected the composer's study of the American minimalists. The work elicited shouts and whistle of admiration from the audience, though I imagine other composers may have been shocked by the audacity of the composer in writing something so direct, a work that could and should compete in terms of audience with works like the Concierto de Aranjuez or other popular classics. Sharon Isbin, here is something for your repertoire or your next CD." (Tom Moore, 2009)

Protocol for determining if it was significant Safety danger flawed because it relied on Flight Attendant to determine level of concern to communicate to pilot and copilot who refused to come out to check out what was a clearly unusual loud consistent alarm like sound coming directly from emergency door in flight.   Crazy as it sounds, flight attendant banged her fist on door at point where you would engage the emergency release!   Then flight attendants not trained in aircraft mechanical evaluation were the ones who were supposed to convey level of threat, despite their not being qualified in such matters.   On top of it all, the attendant huddled together to deny one had banged her fist on door despite two witnesses.   And flight attendant who is a private pilot admitted in video not normal and plane should be checked out.   This was a disturbing disconcerting flight and the safety protocols appear to be flawed, at best.   Spirit and FAA should investigate and determine safety protocols were proper and whether they should be changed.  Flight attendants cannot be counted on to make qualitative engineering mechanical judgments to convey for pilots to make judgments upon.   Passenger safety is at risk if that's the case in my opinion.  Further, it was loud enough to cause hearing problems during descent and after landing.   Federal Aviation Commission should investigate as safety concern.   Horrible flight.  Horrible experience.
